  <h1>TDS under Section 194O on e-commerce operators</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>5 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>Section 194O requires an e-commerce operator to deduct TDS at 0.1% (reduced from 1% with effect from 1 October 2024) on the gross amount of sales of goods or services made through its platform by an e-commerce participant.</b> Individual/HUF participants are exempt up to Rs.5 lakh of annual sales if they furnish PAN/Aadhaar.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">The mechanism</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Rate and exemption</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">194O vs GST TCS (Section 52)</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Practical points</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">The mechanism</h2>
<p>The <b>e-commerce operator</b> (the platform) deducts TDS on the <b>gross amount</b> of sales or services facilitated through it, at the time of credit to the participant or payment, whichever is earlier. This brings online sellers into the tax net at source, independent of who collects the money.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Rate and exemption</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Position</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Rate</td><td>0.1% (reduced from 1% from 1 October 2024)</td></tr><tr><td>Exemption</td><td>Individual/HUF participant: no TDS up to Rs.5 lakh sales p.a., if PAN/Aadhaar furnished</td></tr><tr><td>No PAN/Aadhaar</td><td>TDS at 5% (Section 206AA)</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

  <h2 id="s2">194O vs GST TCS (Section 52)</h2>
<p>194O is an <b>income-tax</b> TDS deducted by the platform on the seller's sales, while <a href="gst-tcs-ecommerce-section-52.html">GST TCS under Section 52</a> is a <b>GST</b> collection on net taxable supplies. Both can apply to the same marketplace transaction, under different laws, and must each be complied with.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">Practical points</h2>
<ul><li>The operator must not also deduct under other TDS sections on the same transaction (194O overrides).</li><li>Sellers should reconcile 194O credit in <a href="form-26as-ais-tis-difference.html">Form 26AS/AIS</a>.</li><li>Report in Form 26Q; issue Form 16A to participants.</li><li>Watch the interaction with 194Q (purchase of goods).</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is the TDS rate under Section 194O?</summary><p>0.1% on the gross sales of an e-commerce participant, reduced from 1% with effect from 1 October 2024 (5% if PAN/Aadhaar is not furnished).</p></details>
    <details><summary>Are small online sellers exempt?</summary><p>Yes. An individual or HUF participant is exempt up to Rs.5 lakh of gross sales in a year, provided PAN or Aadhaar is furnished.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Is 194O the same as GST TCS?</summary><p>No. 194O is income-tax TDS by the platform on the seller's sales, while GST TCS under Section 52 is a GST collection on net taxable supplies; both can apply.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>194O: 0.1% on an e-commerce participant's gross sales.</li><li>Individual/HUF exempt up to Rs.5 lakh with PAN/Aadhaar.</li><li>No PAN/Aadhaar: 5% under Section 206AA.</li><li>Separate from, and additional to, GST TCS under Section 52.</li></ul>
  </div>

